I once heard a preacher tell a church congregation that he'd quit
hanging around some of his old friends because, as he put it &quot;I want to
get around righteous folks!&quot; Why did he not believe these friends of
his were righteous? He mentioned one of them watching &quot;Hell's Box
Office&quot; and &quot;Sin-to-the-Max&quot; on cable TV.

What does this say about that preacher's definition of righteousness?
It is based on a person's performance. And unfortunately many of us
have this idea that our righteousness, or whether God finds us pleasing
to Him, is based on our performance.

The Bible says &quot;4Now when a man works, his wages are not credited to
him as a gift, but as an obligation. 5However, to the man who does not
work but trusts God who justifies the wicked, his faith is credited as
righteousness. 6David says the same thing when he speaks of the
blessedness of the man to whom God credits righteousness apart from
works:
7&quot;Blessed are they
whose transgressions are forgiven,
whose sins are covered.
8Blessed is the man
whose sin the Lord will never count against him.&quot;
Think about that! God credits righteousness to us who believe, apart
from our works! He will never count sin against us! How awesome!

The Bible presents a decidedly non-works-based definition of
righteousness. It's credited to us by God, apart from our works. We're
righteous because God says we are, and that's the end of that
discussion!

Is that a liscence to sin? If you want to look at it that way. I look
at it as a liscence to be accepted by God, a liscence to come into
God's presence and enjoy friendship with Him without my flaws and
imperfections condemning me. The only way I or any of us will ever meet
God's standard of righteousness is if it is creditted to us apart from
our works.

In the passage I quoted above, it says the wages of someone who works
are not considered a gift but an obligation. What would it be like if
you could earn your salvation? If you could earn blessings from God?
Would He get credit or would you? I'm thankful that God has given me as
a gift something so precious, something I could never earn, and all the
glory goes to Him!

