&quot;So do not worry, saying, `What shall we eat?' or `What shall we
drink?' or `What shall we wear?' For the pagans run after all these
things, and your heavenly Father knows that you need them.&quot;

I just looked up the word &quot;pagen&quot; in the dictionary. It simply means
&quot;non-religious&quot;. It used to mean non-Christian. I like the current
definition much better.

It seems to me that the pagans have a great point here!!! I've often
worried about where we'd get money for the next meal and whether or not
our children would have adequate clothing to go to school. I haven't
much worred about a water supply, although many in America do have that
problem right now. I worried continuously when my children were younger
about whether or not we'd live in the slums because I thought Phil
would lose his job. Worry was my constant companion.

As the Lord taught me the definition of &quot;righteousness&quot; - that it IS
Jesus - I started to compare myself with the non-religious. I had, and
still do at times, a lot in common with pagens! A pagen does not run
to God for help and believe that He's with him or her. My worry was and
still is a sign that I am not relying on a &quot;power greater than myself
to restore me to sanity.&quot; (AA: Step 2)

At times, I have a lot of empathy for the non-religious!! Each time I
worry.

In times like that I am thankful that the Biblical definition of the
word &quot;righteousness&quot; has nothing to do with my behavior. Nothing!!!
If it did, my worry would be compounded in that I'd be looking at
myself as never measuring up. I might be thinking, &quot;You must not be a
Christian, Pam, because you worry. You are a pagan.&quot;

Thank God He loves the non-religious. Jesus loves the pagen.

That's because Jesus Christ IS righteousness and we are not!!

Thank GOD!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!! I love you Jesus.

</POST>



