Years ago I proclaimed to a heroin addict that the Lord loves him even
though he was destroying his life. He looked up at me with tears
streaming down his face. He said he didn't expect me to say that. He
expected me to ream him. His mother was furious at me for telling him
how much Jesus loves him. She wanted me to tell him that the Lord
would not put up with him until he cleaned up his act. When I let her
know that I couldn't lie to her son, she went back to her church and
told her friends there that Metro West Outreach OK's sin.

Another time I told a client that Jesus forgave her for her sin of
malicious gossip. The Lord had opened her heart to show her how
destructive gossip is. She was in tears as she pointed out the
specifics of the habit. I proclaimed to her, as is typical for me to
do, that the Lord had not only gifted her with &quot;seeing&quot; how big the
problem of gossip is, but that He also 100% forgave her for it. She
screamed at me! Seriously! &quot;Don't tell me that,&quot; she said, &quot;God is
stupid to forgive me. I need to be punished. I want to keep believing
that God will punish me for my sin because that's the only thing that
will stop me from doing it.&quot; I reminded her that her attempt to
control the problem by rejecting the Lord's forgiveness was obviously
not working. In fact, based on the evidence she had shared, her
problem was getting much worse. She didn't buy that. I never saw her
again.

Neither woman was seeking God's righteousness which would have led them
to understand His love for the sinner.

Today, let's not get sidetracked by staring at our sins, our bad habits
and patterns. In other words, let's not seek after our own
righteousness to solve our problems because we don't have any.

&quot;But seek first . . . HIS righteousness . . . &quot;

Jesus IS righteousness. In HIM we'll not only find forgiveness, but
we'll find His help to overcome things we do to cause problems for
ourselves and others.

Jesus IS righteousness. Not ME! Cool.

</POST>



